                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Okay, so the first thing I did was to do the prime factorization of 1000. It gave me "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{ 2 }^{ 3 }\times { 5 }^{ 3 }"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". Then, with this principle in mind: https://brilliant.org/practice/counting-divisors-2/?p=7 you want to give the first 3 primes (2,3,5) the 3 powers of 4. Knowing that "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":" { 7 }^{ 3 }>{ 11 }\times 13"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" we will then take 7,11 and 13 as our next primes. "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{ 2 }^{ 4 }\times { 3 }^{ 4 }\times { 5 }^{ 4 }\times 7\times 11\times 13=810810000\\ (4+1)\times (4+1)\times (4+1)\times (1+1)\times (1+1)\times (1+1)=1000"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}}]},{"type":"text","text":"



